Definition 4.1. Let $\mathcal{B}$ be an additive category which admits arbitrary filtered colimits. Then: • An object $X\in\mathcal{B}$ is called finitely presentable if the representable functor $\mathcal{B}(X,-):\mathcal{B}\to\mathrm{Ab}$ preserves filtered colimits. • The category $\mathcal{B}$ is called finitely accessible if there is a set $\mathcal{A}$ of finitely presentable objects from $\mathcal{B}$ such that every object in $\mathcal{B}$ is a filtered colimit of objects from $\mathcal{A}$.
Definition 8. A morphism $(Y,q,r,s)\to(Y^{\prime},q^{\prime},r^{\prime},s^{\prime})$ of subdivided composites consists of morphisms $t_{i}:Y_{i}\to Y_{i}^{\prime}$ for $0\leq i\leq n$, such that $q_{1}=q_{1}^{\prime}t_{0}$, $q_{2i}^{\prime}t_{i{-}1}=t_{i}q_{2i}$, $q_{3}=q_{3}^{\prime}t_{n}$, $r_{i}=r_{i}^{\prime}t_{i{-}1}$ and $s_{i}=s_{i}^{\prime}t_{i}$. With compositions inherited from $\mathcal{E}$, one has a category $\textnormal{SdC}(p_{i})_{i}$ of subdivided composites over $(p_{i})_{i}$ and morphisms between them.
Definition 2. Let $g:Z\to A$ and $f:A\to B$ be a composable pair of morphisms in a category $\mathcal{E}$. Then a distributivity pullback around $(f,g)$ is a terminal object of $\textnormal{PB}(f,g)$. When $(p,q,r)$ is a distributivity pullback, we denote this diagramatically as follows: $\xygraph{{X}="tl"[r]{Z}="tm"[r]{A}="tr"[d]{B}="br"[l(2)]{Y}="bl""tl":"tm"^{-}{% p}:"tr"^{-}{g}:"br"^{-}{f}:@{<-}"bl"^{-}{r}:@{<-}"tl"^{-}{q}"tl":@{}"br"|-*{% \scriptstyle{dpb}}}$ and we say that this diagram exhibits $r$ as a distributivity pullback of $g$ along $f$.
Definition 1. Let $g:Z\to A$ and $f:A\to B$ be a composable pair of morphisms in a category $\mathcal{E}$. Then a pullback around $(f,g)$ is a diagram $\xygraph{{X}="tl"[r]{Z}="tm"[r]{A}="tr"[d]{B}="br"[l(2)]{Y}="bl""tl":"tm"^{-}{% p}:"tr"^{-}{g}:"br"^{-}{f}:@{<-}"bl"^{-}{r}:@{<-}"tl"^{-}{q}"tl":@{}"br"|-*{% \scriptstyle{pb}}}$ in which the square with boundary $(gp,f,r,q)$ is, as indicated, a pullback. A morphism $(p,q,r)\to(p^{\prime},q^{\prime},r^{\prime})$ of pullbacks around $(f,g)$ consists of $s:X\to X^{\prime}$ and $t:Y\to Y^{\prime}$ such that $p^{\prime}s=p$, $qs=tq^{\prime}$ and $r=r^{\prime}s$. The category of pullbacks around $(f,g)$ is denoted $\textnormal{PB}(f,g)$.
Definition 9. The associated polynomial of a given subdivided composite $(Y,q,r,s)$ over $(p_{i})_{i}$ is defined to be $\xygraph{{X_{0}}="p1"[r]{Y_{0}}="p2"[r]{Y_{n}}="p3"[r]{X_{n}}="p4""p1":@{<-}"p% 2"^{-}{q_{1}}:"p3"^{-}{q_{2}}:"p4"^{-}{q_{3}}}$ The process of taking associated polynomials is the object map of a functor $\textnormal{ass}:\textnormal{SdC}(p_{i})_{i}\to{\textnormal{\bf Poly}_{% \mathcal{E}}}(X_{0},X_{n}).$
Definition 13. Let $\mathcal{E}$ be a category with pullbacks. A composite of a composable sequence $(p_{i})_{1{\leq}i{\leq}n}$ of polynomials in $\mathcal{E}$, is defined to be the associated polynomial of a terminal object in the category $\textnormal{SdC}(p_{i})_{i}$. When such a composite has been chosen, it is denoted as $p_{n}\circ...\circ p_{1}$.
Definition 7. A subdivided composite over $(p_{i})_{i}$ consists of objects $(Y_{0},...,Y_{n})$, morphisms $\begin{array}[]{lcccr}{q_{1}:Y_{0}\to X_{0}}&&{q_{2,i}:Y_{i{-}1}\to Y_{i}}&&{q% _{3}:Y_{n}\to X_{n}}\end{array}$ for $0<i\leq n$, and morphisms $\begin{array}[]{lccr}{r_{i}:Y_{i{-}1}\to A_{i}}&&&{s_{i}:Y_{i}\to B_{i}}\end{array}$ for $0<i\leq n$, such that $p_{11}r_{1}=q_{1}$, $p_{n3}s_{n}=q_{3}$ and $\xygraph{{\xybox{\xygraph{{Y_{i}}="tl"[r]{A_{i{+}1}}="tr"[d]{X_{i}}="br"[l]{B_% {i}}="bl""tl":"tr"^{-}{r_{i{+}1}}:"br"^{-}{p_{i{+}1,1}}:@{<-}"bl"^{-}{p_{i3}}:% @{<-}"tl"^{-}{s_{i}}:@{}"br"|-{=}}}}[r(3)]{\xybox{\xygraph{{Y_{i{-}1}}="tl"[r]% {Y_{i}}="tr"[d]{B_{i}}="br"[l]{A_{i}}="bl""tl":"tr"^{-}{q_{2i}}:"br"^{-}{s_{i}% }:@{<-}"bl"^{-}{p_{i2}}:@{<-}"tl"^{-}{r_{i}}:@{}"br"|-*{\scriptstyle{pb}}}}}}$
Definition 2.3. Let $\mathcal{G}$ be a 2-group. A left $\mathcal{G}$-module $\mathcal{X}$ is a left $\mathcal{G}$-torsor if $\mathcal{X}$ is nonempty and the characteristic map $\chi=(a,\pi_{2}):\mathcal{G}\times\mathcal{X}\to\mathcal{X}\times\mathcal{X}$ is an equivalence.
Definition 3.5. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a strict monoidal category, and let $\mathcal{X}$ and $\mathcal{Y}$ be strict $\mathcal{C}$-bimodules. A strict morphism from $\mathcal{X}$ to $\mathcal{Y}$ is a strict 2-natural transformation $\mathcal{X}\Rightarrow\mathcal{Y}$.
Definition 5.4. Let $G$ be a group, and let $\mathcal{B}$ be a braided 2-group. Suppose we are given an action $a:G\to\operatorname{Aut}^{\widetilde{\otimes}}(\mathcal{B})$ of $G$ as braided autoequivalences of $\mathcal{B}$. An extension of $G$ by $\mathcal{B}$ with action $a$ is an underlying $2$-group extension $\mathcal{E}$ equipped with an isomorphism between $a\circ\partial:\mathcal{E}\to\operatorname{Aut}^{\otimes}(\mathcal{B})$ and the adjoint action of $\mathcal{E}$ on $\mathcal{B}\cong\partial^{-1}(e)$ which restricts to the trivialization of the adjoint action of $\mathcal{B}$ on itself given by the braiding.
